Paragraph:
&ldquo;Jane, I don&rsquo;t like cavillers or questioners; besides, there is
something truly forbidding in a child taking up her elders in that manner. Be
seated somewhere; and until you can speak pleasantly, remain silent.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Where the dickens is she!&rdquo; he continued. &ldquo;Lizzy!
Georgy! (calling to his sisters) Joan is not here: tell mama she is run out
into the rain&mdash;bad animal!&rdquo;

&ldquo;That is for your impudence in answering mama awhile since,&rdquo; said
he, &ldquo;and for your sneaking way of getting behind curtains, and for the
look you had in your eyes two minutes since, you rat!&rdquo;

&ldquo;Wicked and cruel boy!&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;You are like a
murderer&mdash;you are like a slave-driver&mdash;you are like the Roman
emperors!&rdquo;

&ldquo;What! what!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;Did she say that to me? Did
you hear her, Eliza and Georgiana? Won&rsquo;t I tell mama? but
first&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;For shame! for shame!&rdquo; cried the lady&rsquo;s-maid.
&ldquo;What shocking conduct, Miss Eyre, to strike a young gentleman, your
benefactress&rsquo;s son! Your young master.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You ought to be aware, Miss, that you are under obligations to Mrs.
Reed: she keeps you: if she were to turn you off, you would have to go to the
poorhouse.&rdquo;

Mr. Reed had been dead nine years: it was in this chamber he breathed his last;
here he lay in state; hence his coffin was borne by the undertaker&rsquo;s men;
and, since that day, a sense of dreary consecration had guarded it from
frequent intrusion.

&ldquo;She has screamed out on purpose,&rdquo; declared Abbot, in some disgust.
&ldquo;And what a scream! If she had been in great pain one would have excused
it, but she only wanted to bring us all here: I know her naughty tricks.&rdquo;

I thought so too; and my self-esteem being wounded by the false charge, I
answered promptly, &ldquo;I never cried for such a thing in my life: I hate
going out in the carriage. I cry because I am miserable.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I was knocked down,&rdquo; was the blunt explanation, jerked out of me
by another pang of mortified pride; &ldquo;but that did not make me ill,&rdquo;
I added; while Mr. Lloyd helped himself to a pinch of snuff.

&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you think Gateshead Hall a very beautiful house?&rdquo;
asked he. &ldquo;Are you not very thankful to have such a fine place to live
at?&rdquo;

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know: I asked Aunt Reed once, and she said possibly I
might have some poor, low relations called Eyre, but she knew nothing about
them.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, well! who knows what may happen?&rdquo; said Mr. Lloyd, as he got
up. &ldquo;The child ought to have change of air and scene,&rdquo; he added,
speaking to himself; &ldquo;nerves not in a good state.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; responded Abbot; &ldquo;if she were a nice, pretty child,
one might compassionate her forlornness; but one really cannot care for such a
little toad as that.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t talk to me about her, John: I told you not to go near her;
she is not worthy of notice; I do not choose that either you or your sisters
should associate with her.&rdquo;

&ldquo;My Uncle Reed is in heaven, and can see all you do and think; and so can
papa and mama: they know how you shut me up all day long, and how you wish me
dead.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Troublesome, careless child! and what are you doing now? You look quite
red, as if you had been about some mischief: what were you opening the window
for?&rdquo;

Mrs. Reed occupied her usual seat by the fireside; she made a signal to me to
approach; I did so, and she introduced me to the stony stranger with the words:
&ldquo;This is the little girl respecting whom I applied to you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;So much?&rdquo; was the doubtful answer; and he prolonged his scrutiny
for some minutes. Presently he addressed me&mdash;&ldquo;Your name, little
girl?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No sight so sad as that of a naughty child,&rdquo; he began,
&ldquo;especially a naughty little girl. Do you know where the wicked go after
death?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Benefactress! benefactress!&rdquo; said I inwardly: &ldquo;they all call
Mrs. Reed my benefactress; if so, a benefactress is a disagreeable
thing.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I like Revelations, and the book of Daniel, and Genesis and Samuel, and
a little bit of Exodus, and some parts of Kings and Chronicles, and Job and
Jonah.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That proves you have a wicked heart; and you must pray to God to change
it: to give you a new and clean one: to take away your heart of stone and give
you a heart of flesh.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Deceit is, indeed, a sad fault in a child,&rdquo; said Mr. Brocklehurst;
&ldquo;it is akin to falsehood, and all liars will have their portion in the
lake burning with fire and brimstone; she shall, however, be watched, Mrs.
Reed. I will speak to Miss Temple and the teachers.&rdquo;

&ldquo;This is the state of things I quite approve,&rdquo; returned Mrs. Reed;
&ldquo;had I sought all England over, I could scarcely have found a system more
exactly fitting a child like Jane Eyre. Consistency, my dear Mr. Brocklehurst;
I advocate consistency in all things.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Consistency, madam, is the first of Christian duties; and it has been
observed in every arrangement connected with the establishment of Lowood: plain
fare, simple attire, unsophisticated accommodations, hardy and active habits;
such is the order of the day in the house and its inhabitants.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Quite right, sir. I may then depend upon this child being received as a
pupil at Lowood, and there being trained in conformity to her position and
prospects?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Madam, you may: she shall be placed in that nursery of chosen plants,
and I trust she will show herself grateful for the inestimable privilege of her
election.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I will send her, then, as soon as possible, Mr. Brocklehurst; for, I
assure you, I feel anxious to be relieved of a responsibility that was becoming
too irksome.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am not deceitful: if I were, I should say I loved <i>you;</i> but I
declare I do not love you: I dislike you the worst of anybody in the world
except John Reed; and this book about the liar, you may give to your girl,
Georgiana, for it is she who tells lies, and not I.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Not you. You told Mr. Brocklehurst I had a bad character, a deceitful
disposition; and I&rsquo;ll let everybody at Lowood know what you are, and what
you have done.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You are a strange child, Miss Jane,&rdquo; she said, as she looked down
at me; &ldquo;a little roving, solitary thing: and you are going to school, I
suppose?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, I will; but mind you are a very good girl, and don&rsquo;t be
afraid of me. Don&rsquo;t start when I chance to speak rather sharply;
it&rsquo;s so provoking.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think I shall ever be afraid of you again, Bessie, because
I have got used to you, and I shall soon have another set of people to
dread.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Just now! and rather! How coolly my little lady says it! I dare say now
if I were to ask you for a kiss you wouldn&rsquo;t give it me: you&rsquo;d say
you&rsquo;d <i>rather</i> not.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, Bessie: she came to my crib last night when you were gone down to
supper, and said I need not disturb her in the morning, or my cousins either;
and she told me to remember that she had always been my best friend, and to
speak of her and be grateful to her accordingly.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The child is very young to be sent alone,&rdquo; said she, putting her
candle down on the table. She considered me attentively for a minute or two,
then further added&mdash;

&ldquo;And hungry too, no doubt: let her have some supper before she goes to
bed, Miss Miller. Is this the first time you have left your parents to come to
school, my little girl?&rdquo;

&ldquo;You had this morning a breakfast which you could not eat; you must be
hungry:&mdash;I have ordered that a lunch of bread and cheese shall be served
to all.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It is partly a charity-school: you and I, and all the rest of us, are
charity-children. I suppose you are an orphan: are not either your father or
your mother dead?&rdquo;

&ldquo;To Miss Temple? Oh, no! I wish it did: she has to answer to Mr.
Brocklehurst for all she does. Mr. Brocklehurst buys all our food and all our
clothes.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Burns&rdquo; (such it seems was her name: the girls here were all called
by their surnames, as boys are elsewhere), &ldquo;Burns, you are standing on
the side of your shoe; turn your toes out immediately.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Burns, you poke your chin most unpleasantly; draw it in.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Burns, I insist on your holding your head up; I will not have you before
me in that attitude,&rdquo; &amp;c. &amp;c.

&ldquo;And if I were in your place I should dislike her; I should resist her.
If she struck me with that rod, I should get it from her hand; I should break
it under her nose.&rdquo;

&ldquo;But then it seems disgraceful to be flogged, and to be sent to stand in
the middle of a room full of people; and you are such a great girl: I am far
younger than you, and I could not bear it.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yet it would be your duty to bear it, if you could not avoid it: it is
weak and silly to say you <i>cannot bear</i> what it is your fate to be
required to bear.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Then learn from me, not to judge by appearances: I am, as Miss Scatcherd
said, slatternly; I seldom put, and never keep, things in order; I am careless;
I forget rules; I read when I should learn my lessons; I have no method; and
sometimes I say, like you, I cannot <i>bear</i> to be subjected to systematic
arrangements. This is all very provoking to Miss Scatcherd, who is naturally
neat, punctual, and particular.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Helen Burns, if you don&rsquo;t go and put your drawer in order, and
fold up your work this minute, I&rsquo;ll tell Miss Scatcherd to come and look
at it!&rdquo;

&ldquo;And, ma&rsquo;am,&rdquo; he continued, &ldquo;the laundress tells me
some of the girls have two clean tuckers in the week: it is too much; the rules
limit them to one.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I think I can explain that circumstance, sir. Agnes and Catherine
Johnstone were invited to take tea with some friends at Lowton last Thursday,
and I gave them leave to put on clean tuckers for the occasion.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Madam,&rdquo; he pursued, &ldquo;I have a Master to serve whose kingdom
is not of this world: my mission is to mortify in these girls the lusts of the
flesh; to teach them to clothe themselves with shame-facedness and sobriety,
not with braided hair and costly apparel; and each of the young persons before
us has a string of hair twisted in plaits which vanity itself might have woven;
these, I repeat, must be cut off; think of the time wasted, of&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;If all the world hated you, and believed you wicked, while your own
conscience approved you, and absolved you from guilt, you would not be without
friends.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, ma&rsquo;am; she was sorry to have to do it: but my uncle, as I have
often heard the servants say, got her to promise before he died that she would
always keep me.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I know something of Mr. Lloyd; I shall write to him; if his reply agrees
with your statement, you shall be publicly cleared from every imputation; to
me, Jane, you are clear now.&rdquo;

Miss Temple got up, took her hand and examined her pulse; then she returned to
her own seat: as she resumed it, I heard her sigh low. She was pensive a few
minutes, then rousing herself, she said cheerfully&mdash;

&ldquo;Barbara,&rdquo; she said to the servant who answered it, &ldquo;I have
not yet had tea; bring the tray and place cups for these two young
ladies.&rdquo;

&ldquo;How sad to be lying now on a sick bed, and to be in danger of dying!
This world is pleasant&mdash;it would be dreary to be called from it, and to
have to go who knows where?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, no, Helen!&rdquo; I stopped, distressed. While I tried to devour my
tears, a fit of coughing seized Helen; it did not, however, wake the nurse;
when it was over, she lay some minutes exhausted; then she whispered&mdash;

&ldquo;I am sure there is a future state; I believe God is good; I can resign
my immortal part to Him without any misgiving. God is my father; God is my
friend: I love Him; I believe He loves me.&rdquo;

&ldquo;How comfortable I am! That last fit of coughing has tired me a little; I
feel as if I could sleep: but don&rsquo;t leave me, Jane; I like to have you
near me.&rdquo;

Her grave is in Brocklebridge churchyard: for fifteen years after her death it
was only covered by a grassy mound; but now a grey marble tablet marks the
spot, inscribed with her name, and the word &ldquo;Resurgam.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Miss,&rdquo; said a servant who met me in the lobby, where I was
wandering like a troubled spirit, &ldquo;a person below wishes to see
you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The carrier, no doubt,&rdquo; I thought, and ran downstairs without
inquiry. I was passing the back-parlour or teachers&rsquo; sitting-room, the
door of which was half open, to go to the kitchen, when some one ran out&mdash;

&ldquo;Well, who is it?&rdquo; she asked, in a voice and with a smile I half
recognised; &ldquo;you&rsquo;ve not quite forgotten me, I think, Miss
Jane?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes; nearly five years since to Robert Leaven, the coachman; and
I&rsquo;ve a little girl besides Bobby there, that I&rsquo;ve christened
Jane.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Missis looks stout and well enough in the face, but I think she&rsquo;s
not quite easy in her mind: Mr. John&rsquo;s conduct does not please
her&mdash;he spends a deal of money.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, Miss Jane, not exactly: you are genteel enough; you look like a
lady, and it is as much as ever I expected of you: you were no beauty as a
child.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The Miss Reeds could not play as well!&rdquo; said she exultingly.
&ldquo;I always said you would surpass them in learning: and can you
draw?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, that is beautiful, Miss Jane! It is as fine a picture as any Miss
Reed&rsquo;s drawing-master could paint, let alone the young ladies themselves,
who could not come near it: and have you learnt French?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes; he did not stay many minutes in the house: Missis was very high
with him; she called him afterwards a &lsquo;sneaking tradesman.&rsquo;
My Robert believes he was a wine-merchant.&rdquo;

The roads were heavy, the night misty; my conductor let his horse walk all the
way, and the hour and a half extended, I verily believe, to two hours; at last
he turned in his seat and said&mdash;

&ldquo;Oh, it is no trouble; I dare say your own hands are almost numbed with
cold. Leah, make a little hot negus and cut a sandwich or two: here are the
keys of the storeroom.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Now, then, draw nearer to the fire,&rdquo; she continued.
&ldquo;You&rsquo;ve brought your luggage with you, haven&rsquo;t you, my
dear?&rdquo;

AdÃ¨le sang the canzonette tunefully enough, and with the
<i>na&iuml;vetÃ©</i> of her age. This achieved, she jumped from my knee
and said, &ldquo;Now, Mademoiselle, I will repeat you some poetry.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes; this is the dining-room. I have just opened the window, to let in a
little air and sunshine; for everything gets so damp in apartments that are
seldom inhabited; the drawing-room yonder feels like a vault.&rdquo;

&ldquo;In what order you keep these rooms, Mrs. Fairfax!&rdquo; said I.
&ldquo;No dust, no canvas coverings: except that the air feels chilly, one
would think they were inhabited daily.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, yes; the family have always been respected here. Almost all the land
in this neighbourhood, as far as you can see, has belonged to the Rochesters
time out of mind.&rdquo;

&ldquo;<i>I</i> have no cause to do otherwise than like him; and I believe he
is considered a just and liberal landlord by his tenants: but he has never
lived much amongst them.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No; they occupy a range of smaller apartments to the back; no one ever
sleeps here: one would almost say that, if there were a ghost at Thornfield
Hall, this would be its haunt.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I believe not. And yet it is said the Rochesters have been rather a
violent than a quiet race in their time: perhaps, though, that is the reason
they rest tranquilly in their graves now.&rdquo;

The conversation, thus turned on AdÃ¨le, continued till we reached the
light and cheerful region below. AdÃ¨le came running to meet us in the
hall, exclaiming&mdash;

&ldquo;Thank you: I shall do: I have no broken bones,&mdash;only a
sprain;&rdquo; and again he stood up and tried his foot, but the result
extorted an involuntary &ldquo;Ugh!&rdquo;

&ldquo;From just below; and I am not at all afraid of being out late when it is
moonlight: I will run over to Hay for you with pleasure, if you wish it:
indeed, I am going there to post a letter.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I see,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;the mountain will never be brought to
Mahomet, so all you can do is to aid Mahomet to go to the mountain; I must beg
of you to come here.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes, and Miss AdÃ¨le; they are in the dining-room, and John is
gone for a surgeon; for master has had an accident; his horse fell and his
ankle is sprained.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Mr. Rochester would be glad if you and your pupil would take tea with
him in the drawing-room this evening,&rdquo; said she: &ldquo;he has been so
much engaged all day that he could not ask to see you before.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, at six o&rsquo;clock: he keeps early hours in the country. You had
better change your frock now; I will go with you and fasten it. Here is a
candle.&rdquo;

Mr. Rochester must have been aware of the entrance of Mrs. Fairfax and myself;
but it appeared he was not in the mood to notice us, for he never lifted his
head as we approached.

&ldquo;I should be obliged to take time, sir, before I could give you an answer
worthy of your acceptance: a present has many faces to it, has it not? and one
should consider all, before pronouncing an opinion as to its nature.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Miss Eyre, you are not so unsophisticated as AdÃ¨le: she demands a
&lsquo;cadeau,&rsquo; clamorously, the moment she sees me: you beat about the
bush.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, don&rsquo;t fall back on over-modesty! I have examined AdÃ¨le,
and find you have taken great pains with her: she is not bright, she has no
talents; yet in a short time she has made much improvement.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Sir, you have now given me my &lsquo;cadeau;&rsquo; I am obliged to you:
it is the meed teachers most covet&mdash;praise of their pupils&rsquo;
progress.&rdquo;

&ldquo;For the men in green: it was a proper moonlight evening for them.
Did I break through one of your rings, that you spread that damned ice on the
causeway?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t trouble yourself to give her a character,&rdquo; returned
Mr. Rochester: &ldquo;eulogiums will not bias me; I shall judge for myself. She
began by felling my horse.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You have lived the life of a nun: no doubt you are well drilled in
religious forms;&mdash;Brocklehurst, who I understand directs Lowood, is a
parson, is he not?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Of course: that is the established answer. Go into the library&mdash;I
mean, if you please.&mdash;(Excuse my tone of command; I am used to say,
&lsquo;Do this,&rsquo; and it is done: I cannot alter my customary habits for
one new inmate.)&mdash;Go, then, into the library; take a candle with you;
leave the door open; sit down to the piano, and play a tune.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Enough!&rdquo; he called out in a few minutes. &ldquo;You play <i>a
little</i>, I see; like any other English school-girl; perhaps rather better
than some, but not well.&rdquo;

&ldquo;AdÃ¨le showed me some sketches this morning, which she said were yours. I
don&rsquo;t know whether they were entirely of your doing; probably a master
aided you?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Ah! that pricks pride. Well, fetch me your portfolio, if you can vouch
for its contents being original; but don&rsquo;t pass your word unless you are
certain: I can recognise patchwork.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I had nothing else to do, because it was the vacation, and I sat at them
from morning till noon, and from noon till night: the length of the midsummer
days favoured my inclination to apply.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Far from it. I was tormented by the contrast between my idea and my
handiwork: in each case I had imagined something which I was quite powerless to
realise.&rdquo;

&ldquo;True: no doubt he may appear so to a stranger, but I am so accustomed to
his manner, I never think of it; and then, if he has peculiarities of temper,
allowance should be made.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Partly because it is his nature&mdash;and we can none of us help our
nature; and partly because he has painful thoughts, no doubt, to harass him,
and make his spirits unequal.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Good evening, madam; I sent to you for a charitable purpose. I have
forbidden AdÃ¨le to talk to me about her presents, and she is bursting
with repletion; have the goodness to serve her as auditress and interlocutrice;
it will be one of the most benevolent acts you ever performed.&rdquo;

I should, if I had deliberated, have replied to this question by something
conventionally vague and polite; but the answer somehow slipped from my tongue
before I was aware&mdash;&ldquo;No, sir.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am willing to amuse you, if I can, sir&mdash;quite willing; but I
cannot introduce a topic, because how do I know what will interest you?
Ask me questions, and I will do my best to answer them.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think, sir, you have a right to command me, merely because
you are older than I, or because you have seen more of the world than I have;
your claim to superiority depends on the use you have made of your time and
experience.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I was thinking, sir, that very few masters would trouble themselves to
inquire whether or not their paid subordinates were piqued and hurt by their
orders.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Paid subordinates! What! you are my paid subordinate, are you? Oh yes, I
had forgotten the salary! Well then, on that mercenary ground, will you agree
to let me hector a little?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, sir, not on that ground; but, on the ground that you did forget it,
and that you care whether or not a dependent is comfortable in his dependency,
I agree heartily.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am sure, sir, I should never mistake informality for insolence: one I
rather like, the other nothing free-born would submit to, even for a
salary.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And so may you,&rdquo; I thought. My eye met his as the idea crossed my
mind: he seemed to read the glance, answering as if its import had been spoken
as well as imagined&mdash;

&ldquo;Possibly: yet why should I, if I can get sweet, fresh pleasure?
And I may get it as sweet and fresh as the wild honey the bee gathers on the
moor.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Once more, how do you know? By what instinct do you pretend to
distinguish between a fallen seraph of the abyss and a messenger from the
eternal throne&mdash;between a guide and a seducer?&rdquo;

&ldquo;I judged by your countenance, sir, which was troubled when you said the
suggestion had returned upon you. I feel sure it will work you more misery if
you listen to it.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Not at all&mdash;it bears the most gracious message in the world: for
the rest, you are not my conscience-keeper, so don&rsquo;t make yourself
uneasy. Here, come in, bonny wanderer!&rdquo;

&ldquo;Now,&rdquo; he continued, again addressing me, &ldquo;I have received
the pilgrim&mdash;a disguised deity, as I verily believe. Already it has done
me good: my heart was a sort of charnel; it will now be a shrine.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am laying down good intentions, which I believe durable as flint.
Certainly, my associates and pursuits shall be other than they have
been.&rdquo;

And spreading out her dress, she chassÃ©ed across the room till, having
reached Mr. Rochester, she wheeled lightly round before him on tip-toe, then
dropped on one knee at his feet, exclaiming&mdash;

&ldquo;Monsieur, je vous remercie mille fois de votre bontÃ©;&rdquo; then
rising, she added, &ldquo;C&rsquo;est comme cela que maman faisait,
n&rsquo;est-ce pas, monsieur?&rdquo;

Here ensued a pause, filled up by the producing and lighting of a cigar; having
placed it to his lips and breathed a trail of Havannah incense on the freezing
and sunless air, he went on&mdash;

&ldquo;&lsquo;I will like it,&rsquo; said I; &lsquo;I dare like it;&rsquo;
and&rdquo; (he subjoined moodily) &ldquo;I will keep my word; I will break
obstacles to happiness, to goodness&mdash;yes, goodness. I wish to be a better
man than I have been, than I am; as Job&rsquo;s leviathan broke the spear, the
dart, and the habergeon, hindrances which others count as iron and brass, I
will esteem but straw and rotten wood.&rdquo;

&ldquo;In the name of all the elves in Christendom, is that Jane Eyre?&rdquo;
he demanded. &ldquo;What have you done with me, witch, sorceress? Who is
in the room besides you? Have you plotted to drown me?&rdquo;

&ldquo;I will fetch you a candle, sir; and, in Heaven&rsquo;s name, get up.
Somebody has plotted something: you cannot too soon find out who and what it
is.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There! I am up now; but at your peril you fetch a candle yet: wait two
minutes till I get into some dry garments, if any dry there be&mdash;yes, here
is my dressing-gown. Now run!&rdquo;

He re-entered, pale and very gloomy. &ldquo;I have found it all out,&rdquo;
said he, setting his candle down on the washstand; &ldquo;it is as I
thought.&rdquo;

&ldquo;A strange affair!&rdquo; I said, in a low voice: then, looking at her
fixedly&mdash;&ldquo;Did Mr. Rochester wake nobody? Did no one hear him
move?&rdquo;

She again raised her eyes to me, and this time there was something of
consciousness in their expression. She seemed to examine me warily; then she
answered&mdash;

&ldquo;Qu&rsquo;avez-vous, mademoiselle?&rdquo; said she. &ldquo;Vos doigts
tremblent comme la feuille, et vos joues sont rouges: mais, rouges comme des
cerises!&rdquo;

&ldquo;You must want your tea,&rdquo; said the good lady, as I joined her;
&ldquo;you ate so little at dinner. I am afraid,&rdquo; she continued,
&ldquo;you are not well to-day: you look flushed and feverish.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It is fair to-night,&rdquo; said she, as she looked through the panes,
&ldquo;though not starlight; Mr. Rochester has, on the whole, had a favourable
day for his journey.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes, indeed: and not only for her beauty, but for her accomplishments.
She was one of the ladies who sang: a gentleman accompanied her on the piano.
She and Mr. Rochester sang a duet.&rdquo;

&ldquo;A very rich and powerful one: she sang delightfully; it was a treat to
listen to her;&mdash;and she played afterwards. I am no judge of music, but Mr.
Rochester is; and I heard him say her execution was remarkably good.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It appears not: I fancy neither she nor her sister have very large
fortunes. Old Lord Ingram&rsquo;s estates were chiefly entailed, and the eldest
son came in for everything almost.&rdquo;

&ldquo;True: yet I should scarcely fancy Mr. Rochester would entertain an idea
of the sort. But you eat nothing: you have scarcely tasted since you began
tea.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It is from the master,&rdquo; said she, as she looked at the direction.
&ldquo;Now I suppose we shall know whether we are to expect his return or
not.&rdquo;

Ere I permitted myself to request an explanation, I tied the string of
AdÃ¨le&rsquo;s pinafore, which happened to be loose: having helped her
also to another bun and refilled her mug with milk, I said, nonchalantly&mdash;

&ldquo;Ah!&mdash;she understands what she has to do,&mdash;nobody
better,&rdquo; rejoined Leah significantly; &ldquo;and it is not every one
could fill her shoes&mdash;not for all the money she gets.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, indeed, I don&rsquo;t; Mr. Rochester has something else to think
about. Never mind the ladies to-night; perhaps you will see them to-morrow:
here is your dinner.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You said it was not likely they should think of being married,&rdquo;
said I, &ldquo;but you see Mr. Rochester evidently prefers her to any of the
other ladies.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And she him,&rdquo; I added; &ldquo;look how she leans her head towards
him as if she were conversing confidentially; I wish I could see her face; I
have never had a glimpse of it yet.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I will not give him that trouble,&rdquo; I answered. &ldquo;I will go,
if no better may be; but I don&rsquo;t like it. Shall you be there, Mrs.
Fairfax?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Then, what induced you to take charge of such a little doll as
that?&rdquo; (pointing to AdÃ¨le). &ldquo;Where did you pick her
up?&rdquo;

&ldquo;My dearest, don&rsquo;t mention governesses; the word makes me nervous.
I have suffered a martyrdom from their incompetency and caprice. I thank Heaven
I have now done with them!&rdquo;

Mrs. Dent here bent over to the pious lady and whispered something in her ear;
I suppose, from the answer elicited, it was a reminder that one of the
anathematised race was present.

&ldquo;Certainly, my best. And I was quite right: depend on that: there are a
thousand reasons why liaisons between governesses and tutors should never be
tolerated a moment in any well-regulated house; firstly&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, never: we might do what we pleased; ransack her desk and her
workbox, and turn her drawers inside out; and she was so good-natured, she
would give us anything we asked for.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Pardon me, madam: no need of explanation; your own fine sense must
inform you that one of your frowns would be a sufficient substitute for capital
punishment.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Do you know,&rdquo; said she, &ldquo;that, of the three characters, I
liked you in the last best? Oh, had you but lived a few years earlier, what a
gallant gentleman-highwayman you would have made!&rdquo;

It was verging on dusk, and the clock had already given warning of the hour to
dress for dinner, when little AdÃ¨le, who knelt by me in the drawing-room
window-seat, suddenly exclaimed&mdash;

&ldquo;What can possess him to come home in that style?&rdquo; said Miss
Ingram. &ldquo;He rode Mesrour (the black horse), did he not, when he went out?
and Pilot was with him:&mdash;what has he done with the animals?&rdquo;

He had spoken of Mr. Rochester as an old friend. A curious friendship theirs
must have been: a pointed illustration, indeed, of the old adage that
&ldquo;extremes meet.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And what a sweet-tempered forehead he has!&rdquo; cried
Louisa,&mdash;&ldquo;so smooth&mdash;none of those frowning irregularities I
dislike so much; and such a placid eye and smile!&rdquo;

&ldquo;But I cannot persuade her to go away, my lady,&rdquo; said the footman;
&ldquo;nor can any of the servants: Mrs. Fairfax is with her just now,
entreating her to be gone; but she has taken a chair in the chimney-corner, and
says nothing shall stir her from it till she gets leave to come in here.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It is too fine,&rdquo; said she. &ldquo;I can make nothing of such a
hand as that; almost without lines: besides, what is in a palm? Destiny is not
written there.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, I have not much choice! They generally run on the same
theme&mdash;courtship; and promise to end in the same
catastrophe&mdash;marriage.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Nothing to you? When a lady, young and full of life and health, charming
with beauty and endowed with the gifts of rank and fortune, sits and smiles in
the eyes of a gentleman you&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;I was talking of ladies smiling in the eyes of gentlemen; and of late so
many smiles have been shed into Mr. Rochester&rsquo;s eyes that they overflow
like two cups filled above the brim: have you never remarked that?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No question about his right: but have you never observed that, of all
the tales told here about matrimony, Mr. Rochester has been favoured with the
most lively and the most continuous?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No; some unaccountable one. In short, I believe you have been trying to
draw me out&mdash;or in; you have been talking nonsense to make me talk
nonsense. It is scarcely fair, sir.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I cannot tell till I have thought it all over. If, on reflection, I find
I have fallen into no great absurdity, I shall try to forgive you; but it was
not right.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I had better not stay long, sir; it must be near eleven o&rsquo;clock.
Oh, are you aware, Mr. Rochester, that a stranger has arrived here since you
left this morning?&rdquo;

&ldquo;My little friend!&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;I wish I were in a quiet island
with only you; and trouble, and danger, and hideous recollections removed from
me.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Fetch me now, Jane, a glass of wine from the dining-room: they will be
at supper there; and tell me if Mason is with them, and what he is
doing.&rdquo;

He half smiled. &ldquo;But if I were to go to them, and they only looked at me
coldly, and whispered sneeringly amongst each other, and then dropped off and
left me one by one, what then? Would you go with them?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Go back now into the room; step quietly up to Mason, and whisper in his
ear that Mr. Rochester is come and wishes to see him: show him in here and then
leave me.&rdquo;

At a late hour, after I had been in bed some time, I heard the visitors repair
to their chambers: I distinguished Mr. Rochester&rsquo;s voice, and heard him
say, &ldquo;This way, Mason; this is your room.&rdquo;

&ldquo;All&rsquo;s right!&mdash;all&rsquo;s right!&rdquo; he cried.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a mere rehearsal of Much Ado about Nothing. Ladies, keep off,
or I shall wax dangerous.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Now, Carter, be on the alert,&rdquo; he said to this last: &ldquo;I give
you but half-an-hour for dressing the wound, fastening the bandages, getting
the patient downstairs and all.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Not a whit!&mdash;courage! This day fortnight you&rsquo;ll hardly be a
pin the worse of it: you&rsquo;ve lost a little blood; that&rsquo;s all.
Carter, assure him there&rsquo;s no danger.&rdquo;

&ldquo;But under such circumstances, what could one do?&rdquo; returned Mason.
&ldquo;Oh, it was frightful!&rdquo; he added, shuddering. &ldquo;And I
did not expect it: she looked so quiet at first.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You will when you are out of the country: when you get back to Spanish
Town, you may think of her as dead and buried&mdash;or rather, you need not
think of her at all.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Now,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;go to the other side of the bed while I
order his toilet; but don&rsquo;t leave the room: you may be wanted
again.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Now, I&rsquo;ve another errand for you,&rdquo; said my untiring master;
&ldquo;you must away to my room again. What a mercy you are shod with velvet,
Jane!&mdash;a clod-hopping messenger would never do at this juncture. You must
open the middle drawer of my toilet-table and take out a little phial and a
little glass you will find there,&mdash;quick!&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am sure you do. Now, Jane, trip on before us away to the backstairs;
unbolt the side-passage door, and tell the driver of the post-chaise you will
see in the yard&mdash;or just outside, for I told him not to drive his rattling
wheels over the pavement&mdash;to be ready; we are coming: and, Jane, if any
one is about, come to the foot of the stairs and hem.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Take care of him,&rdquo; said Mr. Rochester to the latter, &ldquo;and
keep him at your house till he is quite well: I shall ride over in a day or two
to see how he gets on. Richard, how is it with you?&rdquo;

&ldquo;The glamour of inexperience is over your eyes,&rdquo; he answered;
&ldquo;and you see it through a charmed medium: you cannot discern that the
gilding is slime and the silk draperies cobwebs; that the marble is sordid
slate, and the polished woods mere refuse chips and scaly bark. Now
<i>here</i>&rdquo; (he pointed to the leafy enclosure we had entered)
&ldquo;all is real, sweet, and pure.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Do you like this sunrise, Jane? That sky with its high and light clouds
which are sure to melt away as the day waxes warm&mdash;this placid and balmly
atmosphere?&rdquo;

&ldquo;But I had fastened the door&mdash;I had the key in my pocket: I should
have been a careless shepherd if I had left a lamb&mdash;my pet lamb&mdash;so
near a wolf&rsquo;s den, unguarded: you were safe.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I cannot vouch for that till Mason is out of England: nor even then. To
live, for me, Jane, is to stand on a crater-crust which may crack and spue fire
any day.&rdquo;

&ldquo;But Mr. Mason seems a man easily led. Your influence, sir, is evidently
potent with him: he will never set you at defiance or wilfully injure
you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, no! Mason will not defy me; nor, knowing it, will he hurt
me&mdash;but, unintentionally, he might in a moment, by one careless word,
deprive me, if not of life, yet for ever of happiness.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Sit,&rdquo; he said; &ldquo;the bench is long enough for two. You
don&rsquo;t hesitate to take a place at my side, do you? Is that wrong,
Jane?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Jane, Jane,&rdquo; said he, stopping before me, &ldquo;you are quite
pale with your vigils: don&rsquo;t you curse me for disturbing your
rest?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Shake hands in confirmation of the word. What cold fingers! They
were warmer last night when I touched them at the door of the mysterious
chamber. Jane, when will you watch with me again?&rdquo;

&ldquo;For instance, the night before I am married! I am sure I shall not be
able to sleep. Will you promise to sit up with me to bear me company? To you I
can talk of my lovely one: for now you have seen her and know her.&rdquo;

&ldquo;A strapper&mdash;a real strapper, Jane: big, brown, and buxom; with hair
just such as the ladies of Carthage must have had. Bless me! there&rsquo;s Dent
and Lynn in the stables! Go in by the shrubbery, through that wicket.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I daresay you hardly remember me, Miss,&rdquo; he said, rising as I
entered; &ldquo;but my name is Leaven: I lived coachman with Mrs. Reed when you
were at Gateshead, eight or nine years since, and I live there still.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, Robert! how do you do? I remember you very well: you used to give me
a ride sometimes on Miss Georgiana&rsquo;s bay pony. And how is Bessie? You are
married to Bessie?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes, Miss: my wife is very hearty, thank you; she brought me another
little one about two months since&mdash;we have three now&mdash;and both mother
and child are thriving.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Why, you see, Miss Eyre, it is not a common mishap: his life has been
very wild: these last three years he gave himself up to strange ways, and his
death was shocking.&rdquo;

&ldquo;John Reed is dead, too, sir: he ruined himself and half-ruined his
family, and is supposed to have committed suicide. The news so shocked his
mother that it brought on an apoplectic attack.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And what good can you do her? Nonsense, Jane! I would never think of
running a hundred miles to see an old lady who will, perhaps, be dead before
you reach her: besides, you say she cast you off.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I shall be glad so to do, sir, if you, in your turn, will promise that I
and AdÃ¨le shall be both safe out of the house before your bride enters
it.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes, she is alive; and more sensible and collected than she was.
The doctor says she may linger a week or two yet; but he hardly thinks she will
finally recover.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Of course not. Georgiana and she had nothing in common: they never had
had. She would not be burdened with her society for any consideration.
Georgiana should take her own course; and she, Eliza, would take hers.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Who&mdash;I?&rdquo; was her answer. &ldquo;Who are you?&rdquo; looking
at me with surprise and a sort of alarm, but still not wildly. &ldquo;You
are quite a stranger to me&mdash;where is Bessie?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Aunt,&rdquo; she repeated. &ldquo;Who calls me aunt? You are not one of
the Gibsons; and yet I know you&mdash;that face, and the eyes and forehead, are
quiet familiar to me: you are like&mdash;why, you are like Jane Eyre!&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, I have twice done you a wrong which I regret now. One was in
breaking the promise which I gave my husband to bring you up as my own child;
the other&mdash;&rdquo; she stopped. &ldquo;After all, it is of no great
importance, perhaps,&rdquo; she murmured to herself: &ldquo;and then I may get
better; and to humble myself so to her is painful.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, I must get it over. Eternity is before me: I had better tell
her.&mdash;Go to my dressing-case, open it, and take out a letter you will see
there.&rdquo;

&ldquo;My disposition is not so bad as you think: I am passionate, but not
vindictive. Many a time, as a little child, I should have been glad to love you
if you would have let me; and I long earnestly to be reconciled to you now:
kiss me, aunt.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Love me, then, or hate me, as you will,&rdquo; I said at last,
&ldquo;you have my full and free forgiveness: ask now for God&rsquo;s, and be
at peace.&rdquo;

I neither expressed surprise at this resolution nor attempted to dissuade her
from it. &ldquo;The vocation will fit you to a hair,&rdquo; I thought:
&ldquo;much good may it do you!&rdquo;

&ldquo;It would be past the power of magic, sir;&rdquo; and, in thought, I
added, &ldquo;A loving eye is all the charm needed: to such you are handsome
enough; or rather your sternness has a power beyond beauty.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Pass, Janet,&rdquo; said he, making room for me to cross the stile:
&ldquo;go up home, and stay your weary little wandering feet at a
friend&rsquo;s threshold.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Thank you, Mr. Rochester, for your great kindness. I am strangely glad
to get back again to you: and wherever you are is my home&mdash;my only
home.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Look at his wings,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;he reminds me rather of a West
Indian insect; one does not often see so large and gay a night-rover in
England; there! he is flown.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Turn back: on so lovely a night it is a shame to sit in the house; and
surely no one can wish to go to bed while sunset is thus at meeting with
moonrise.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Jane,&rdquo; he recommenced, as we entered the laurel walk, and slowly
strayed down in the direction of the sunk fence and the horse-chestnut,
&ldquo;Thornfield is a pleasant place in summer, is it not?&rdquo;

&ldquo;You must have become in some degree attached to the house,&mdash;you,
who have an eye for natural beauties, and a good deal of the organ of
Adhesiveness?&rdquo;

&ldquo;And though I don&rsquo;t comprehend how it is, I perceive you have
acquired a degree of regard for that foolish little child AdÃ¨le, too;
and even for simple dame Fairfax?&rdquo;

&ldquo;In about a month I hope to be a bridegroom,&rdquo; continued Mr.
Rochester; &ldquo;and in the interim, I shall myself look out for employment
and an asylum for you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It is a long way to Ireland, Janet, and I am sorry to send my little
friend on such weary travels: but if I can&rsquo;t do better, how is it to be
helped? Are you anything akin to me, do you think, Jane?&rdquo;

&ldquo;As we are!&rdquo; repeated Mr. Rochester&mdash;&ldquo;so,&rdquo; he
added, enclosing me in his arms, gathering me to his breast, pressing his lips
on my lips: &ldquo;so, Jane!&rdquo;

&ldquo;My bride is here,&rdquo; he said, again drawing me to him,
&ldquo;because my equal is here, and my likeness. Jane, will you marry
me?&rdquo;

&ldquo;How can I do that? If you are true, and your offer real, my only
feelings to you must be gratitude and devotion&mdash;they cannot
torture.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Gratitude!&rdquo; he ejaculated; and added wildly&mdash;&ldquo;Jane
accept me quickly. Say, Edward&mdash;give me my name&mdash;Edward&mdash;I will
marry you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Come to me&mdash;come to me entirely now,&rdquo; said he; and added, in
his deepest tone, speaking in my ear as his cheek was laid on mine, &ldquo;Make
my happiness&mdash;I will make yours.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh, sir!&mdash;never rain jewels! I don&rsquo;t like to hear them spoken
of. Jewels for Jane Eyre sounds unnatural and strange: I would rather not have
them.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, no, sir! think of other subjects, and speak of other things, and in
another strain. Don&rsquo;t address me as if I were a beauty; I am your plain,
Quakerish governess.&rdquo;

I laughed at him as he said this. &ldquo;I am not an angel,&rdquo; I asserted;
&ldquo;and I will not be one till I die: I will be myself. Mr. Rochester, you
must neither expect nor exact anything celestial of me&mdash;for you will not
get it, any more than I shall get it of you: which I do not at all
anticipate.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Distasteful! and like you again! I think I shall like you again, and yet
again: and I will make you confess I do not only <i>like</i>, but <i>love</i>
you&mdash;with truth, fervour, constancy.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Not at all, sir; I ask only this: don&rsquo;t send for the jewels, and
don&rsquo;t crown me with roses: you might as well put a border of gold lace
round that plain pocket handkerchief you have there.&rdquo;

He looked disturbed. &ldquo;What? what?&rdquo; he said hastily.
&ldquo;Curiosity is a dangerous petition: it is well I have not taken a vow to
accord every request&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;You are welcome to all my confidence that is worth having, Jane; but for
God&rsquo;s sake, don&rsquo;t desire a useless burden! Don&rsquo;t long for
poison&mdash;don&rsquo;t turn out a downright Eve on my hands!&rdquo;

&ldquo;If that will be <i>your</i> married look, I, as a Christian, will soon
give up the notion of consorting with a mere sprite or salamander. But what had
you to ask, thing,&mdash;out with it?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, I feigned courtship of Miss Ingram, because I wished to render you
as madly in love with me as I was with you; and I knew jealousy would be the
best ally I could call in for the furtherance of that end.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Excellent! Now you are small&mdash;not one whit bigger than the end of
my little finger. It was a burning shame and a scandalous disgrace to act in
that way. Did you think nothing of Miss Ingram&rsquo;s feelings, sir?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Never mind, Mr. Rochester: it is in no way interesting to you to know
that. Answer me truly once more. Do you think Miss Ingram will not suffer from
your dishonest coquetry? Won&rsquo;t she feel forsaken and deserted?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Impossible!&mdash;when I told you how she, on the contrary, deserted me:
the idea of my insolvency cooled, or rather extinguished, her flame in a
moment.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Once again, seriously; may I enjoy the great good that has been
vouchsafed to me, without fearing that any one else is suffering the bitter
pain I myself felt a while ago?&rdquo;

&ldquo;That you may, my good little girl: there is not another being in the
world has the same pure love for me as yourself&mdash;for I lay that pleasant
unction to my soul, Jane, a belief in your affection.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I could never have thought it. He is a proud man: all the Rochesters
were proud: and his father, at least, liked money. He, too, has always been
called careful. He means to marry you?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Let me go,&mdash;let me go to Millcote too!&rdquo; she cried.
&ldquo;Mr. Rochester won&rsquo;t: though there is so much room in the new
carriage. Beg him to let me go, mademoiselle.&rdquo;

&ldquo;What is the matter?&rdquo; he asked; &ldquo;all the sunshine is gone. Do
you really wish the bairn to go? Will it annoy you if she is left
behind?&rdquo;

&ldquo;After all, a single morning&rsquo;s interruption will not matter
much,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;when I mean shortly to claim you&mdash;your
thoughts, conversation, and company&mdash;for life.&rdquo;

&ldquo;She is far better as she is,&rdquo; concluded AdÃ¨le, after musing
some time: &ldquo;besides, she would get tired of living with only you in the
moon. If I were mademoiselle, I would never consent to go with you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Why, Jane, what would you have? I fear you will compel me to go through
a private marriage ceremony, besides that performed at the altar. You
will stipulate, I see, for peculiar terms&mdash;what will they be?&rdquo;

Here I heard myself apostrophised as a &ldquo;hard little thing;&rdquo; and it
was added, &ldquo;any other woman would have been melted to marrow at hearing
such stanzas crooned in her praise.&rdquo;

&ldquo;How late it grows!&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;I will run down to the gates:
it is moonlight at intervals; I can see a good way on the road. He may be
coming now, and to meet him will save some minutes of suspense.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, I cannot return to the house,&rdquo; I thought; &ldquo;I cannot
sit by the fireside, while he is abroad in inclement weather: better tire my
limbs than strain my heart; I will go forward and meet him.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There!&rdquo; he exclaimed, as he stretched out his hand and bent from
the saddle: &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t do without me, that is evident. Step on my
boot-toe; give me both hands: mount!&rdquo;

&ldquo;Rain and wind, indeed! Yes, you are dripping like a mermaid; pull my
cloak round you: but I think you are feverish, Jane: both your cheek and hand
are burning hot. I ask again, is there anything the matter?&rdquo;

&ldquo;And on my part likewise,&rdquo; he returned, &ldquo;I have settled
everything; and we shall leave Thornfield to-morrow, within half-an-hour after
our return from church.&rdquo;

&ldquo;With what an extraordinary smile you uttered that word&mdash;&lsquo;very
well,&rsquo; Jane! What a bright spot of colour you have on each cheek! and how
strangely your eyes glitter! Are you well?&rdquo;

&ldquo;I could not, sir: no words could tell you what I feel. I wish this
present hour would never end: who knows with what fate the next may come
charged?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Give me your confidence, Jane,&rdquo; he said: &ldquo;relieve your mind
of any weight that oppresses it, by imparting it to me. What do you
fear?&mdash;that I shall not prove a good husband?&rdquo;

&ldquo;How well you read me, you witch!&rdquo; interposed Mr. Rochester:
&ldquo;but what did you find in the veil besides its embroidery? Did you find
poison, or a dagger, that you look so mournful now?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, sir, I solemnly assure you to the contrary. The shape standing
before me had never crossed my eyes within the precincts of Thornfield Hall
before; the height, the contour were new to me.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It seemed, sir, a woman, tall and large, with thick and dark hair
hanging long down her back. I know not what dress she had on: it was white and
straight; but whether gown, sheet, or shroud, I cannot tell.&rdquo;

&ldquo;This, sir, was purple: the lips were swelled and dark; the brow
furrowed: the black eyebrows widely raised over the bloodshot eyes. Shall I
tell you of what it reminded me?&rdquo;

&ldquo;The creature of an over-stimulated brain; that is certain. I must be
careful of you, my treasure: nerves like yours were not made for rough
handling.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And your previous dreams, were they real too? Is Thornfield Hall a ruin?
Am I severed from you by insuperable obstacles? Am I leaving you without a
tear&mdash;without a kiss&mdash;without a word?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Am I about to do it? Why, the day is already commenced which is to bind
us indissolubly; and when we are once united, there shall be no recurrence of
these mental terrors: I guarantee that.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Mental terrors, sir! I wish I could believe them to be only such: I wish
it more now than ever; since even you cannot explain to me the mystery of that
awful visitant.&rdquo;

&ldquo;We shall not want it to go to church; but it must be ready the moment we
return: all the boxes and luggage arranged and strapped on, and the coachman in
his seat.&rdquo;

At the churchyard wicket he stopped: he discovered I was quite out of breath.
&ldquo;Am I cruel in my love?&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Delay an instant: lean on
me, Jane.&rdquo;

The clergyman looked up at the speaker and stood mute; the clerk did the same;
Mr. Rochester moved slightly, as if an earthquake had rolled under his feet:
taking a firmer footing, and not turning his head or eyes, he said,
&ldquo;Proceed.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The ceremony is quite broken off,&rdquo; subjoined the voice behind us.
&ldquo;I am in a condition to prove my allegation: an insuperable impediment to
this marriage exists.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That&mdash;if a genuine document&mdash;may prove I have been married,
but it does not prove that the woman mentioned therein as my wife is still
